The XIth extract seems to be best explained with Merry and Riddell,²2 as a description of an iceberg. The Phoenician sailors who came to the Cassiterides for tin must have seen many icebergs, descriptions of which they would not fail to give to the Greeks who bought their cargoes. The XIIth extract shows a knowledge of the short summer nights of the northern latitudes, and this must have been obtained too nom the Phoenicians.3

The evidence seems to justify the view that in the ninth century Ro. the Gadhelic branch of the Celtic family was estabh'shed in the British Isles and engaged in the production of tin.
